<subsection xml:id="subsec-basic-operation-of-integers">
    <title>Basic operation of integers</title>
    <introduction>
           <p>
             Basic operation of integers is either addition, subtraction,
             division or multiplication.
          </p>
    </introduction>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-addition-of-integers">
        <title>Addition of integers</title>
          <p>
             Addition means putting numbers together, these numbers can be two or more. 
             Moreover, adding two positive numbers gives a positive result.
          </p>
           <p>
              An example is <m>2+4=6</m>.
           </p>
              <p>
                 While adding a positive to a negative, the result 
                 varries depending on the stronger sign (positive or negative).
              </p>
        <activity>
               <p>
                  <m>\textbf{Work in groups}</m> 
              </p>
               <p>
                 <term>What you need</term>
               </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                         Paper made number line with values from <m>-10</m> to <m>10</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                         Printed worksheets with addition problems.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                          A shared record book.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>       
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                      <li>
                           <p>
                             The teacher to give question papers containing randomized
                             questions.    
                           </p>
                      </li>
                      <li>
                           <p>
                             Each student to attempt the given questions.
                           </p>
                      </li>
                      <li>
                           <p>
                              The teacher to call out each student for provide his or her answer.
                           </p>
                      </li>
                          <li>
                               <p>
                                 Teacher to validate the answers given.
                               </p>
                         </li>
                          <li>
                               <p>
                                 The student with the highest number of correct answers
                                  emerges the winner!
                               </p>
                          </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            </activity>
       <example>
             <statement>
                   <p>
                     Jane bought <m>3000</m> bags of rice in January. In February she 
                     bought an additional <m>430</m> bags of rice. What is the current
                     number of bags of rice she has?
                  </p>
             </statement>
            <solution>
                   <p>
                      <md>
                         <mrow>  \text{January} =\amp 3000\, \text{bags} </mrow>
                         <mrow>  \text{February}=\amp 430\, \text{bags} </mrow>
                         <mrow>       3000 + 430=\amp 3430\, \text{bags} </mrow>
                      </md> 
                  </p>
            </solution>
         </example>
            <example>
             <statement>
                   <p>
                     Evaluate <m>+3+5+8</m> 
                   </p>
             </statement>
                 <solution>
                       <p>
                         Simply add <m>3+5+8=\amp 16</m>
                       </p>
                 </solution>
          </example>
          <example>
                 <statement>
                       <p>
                         During a hiking trip, a group of students recorded their changes in elevation throughout the day.
                         In the morning, they ascended <m>120</m> meters up a hill.Then, they descended <m>85</m> meters into a small valley.
                         After lunch, they climbed up again by <m>40</m> meters, but later slipped and went down by <m>65</m> meters due to a steep slope.
                         What was the group's final elevation change relative to their starting point?       
                       </p>
                 </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>120-85=\amp 35\, \text{meters} </mrow>
                        <mrow>35+40=\amp 75\, \text{meters} </mrow>
                        <mrow>75-65=\amp 10\, \text{meters} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
         </example>
            
       </subsubsection>       

    
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-subtraction-of-integers">
        <title>Subtraction of integers</title>
           <p>
              Subtraction is deducting one number from the other. For instance, if Olivia had
              10 sweets then she ate 3, she remains with 7.
          </p>
           <p>
              In subtraction, having two negative signs in between two integers, give a positive as long as 
             the first integer is a positive one, and the while subtracting a positive integers
             and a negative integer gives a negative result.
           </p>
          <p>
             For example <m>-2-10=-12</m> and <m>3-9=-6</m> 
          </p>
        <activity>
              <p>
                 <m>\textbf{Work in groups}</m> 
              </p>
              <p>
                 <term>What you need</term>
              </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                          <p>
                              Printed work sheets containing a list of expense items such as groceries and 
                             the different amount provided for clearing the expenses.
                          </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>       
            </p>
            <p>
               <ol>
                <li>
                      <p>
                          Each student to show the worked out solution in their books.
                      </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                      Students to share their worked out solutions among themselves and explain to each other
                      how they arrived at the final answer.   
                  </p>
                </li>
               </ol>
            </p>
            </activity>
            <example>
            <statement>
                   <p>
                     Crown harvested <m>12</m> pieces of apples from his farm. After a while, he finds
                     out that <m>4</m> apples are spoilt. How many apples are edible?
                   </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md> 
                      <mrow>12\, \text{apples} - 4\, \text{apples}=\amp 8\, \text{apples}  </mrow>
                    </md> 
                </p>
            </solution>
         </example>
         <example>
            <statement>
                  <p>
                      Solve for : <m>-60-40-20</m>
                  </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                      <md>
                          <mrow>-60-40-20=\amp -120 </mrow>
                      </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
         </example>
            <example>
                 <statement>
                      <p>
                          Solve for : <m>-40--20-10</m>
                       </p>
                 </statement>
                 <solution>
                      <p> <term>HINT : (- -) =  +</term>
                          <md>
                               <mrow> -40+20-10=\amp -30 </mrow>
                         </md>
                      </p>
                 </solution>
            </example>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-multiplication-of-integers">
        <title>Multiplication of integers</title>
           <p>
             Multiplication is defined as repeated addition of a number to itself for 
             the given number of times.
          </p>                
        <activity>
                   <p>
                      <m>\textbf{Work in groups}</m> 
                   </p>
                  <p>
                     <term>What you need</term>
                  </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                      <li>
                           <p>
                             Manually prepared bingo cards  
                           </p>
                      </li>
                      <li>
                          <p>
                              A sheet of paper
                          </p>
                      </li>
                      <li>
                           <p>
                             A pen
                           </p>
                      </li>
                </ul>       
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                     <li>
                           <p>
                             The teacher to create bingo cards with a grid.   
                           </p>
                      </li>
                      <li>
                          <p>
                             Teacher to fill in each square with answers 
                             to the questions being tested.
                          </p>
                     </li>
                      <li>
                           <p>
                              The teacher to call out multiplication problems.
                          </p>
                      </li>
                      <li>
                           <p>
                              Students to look for product of called out problem in the square grid
                             and mark it off.
                           </p>
                      </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                             The first student to get the answer calls out Bingo! And wins
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            </activity>
             <example>
            <statement>
                  <p>
                     Brian earns 450 shillings per day working at a hardware shop.
                     If he works for 22 days in a month,how much money does he earn in that month?
                 </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md> 
                      <mrow>450\, \text{shillings} \times 22  =\amp 9900\, \text{shillings}  </mrow>
                    </md> 
                </p>
            </solution>
         </example>
            <example>
             <statement>
                <p>
                    Evaluate: <m>20 \times 4 \times2</m>
                </p>
             </statement>
             <solution>
                  <p>
                     <md>
                      <mrow> 20 \times 4 \times2 =\amp 160 </mrow>
                      </md>
                   </p>
                </solution>
            </example>
         <example>
             <statement>
                  <p>
                     Solve: <m> -10 \times -2 \times 4</m>
                  </p>
               </statement>
               <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> -10 \times -2=\amp 20 </mrow>
                        <mrow> -20 \times 4=\amp 80 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
               </solution>
         </example>
       
       </subsubsection>       
            
<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-division-of-integers">
        <title>Division of integers</title>
        <p>    
            Division means sharing among a given quantity.
            A basic example is how a mother decides to share oranges she 
            buys among her children, so that each one gets the same number
            of oranges.
        </p>
        <activity>
              <p>
                 <m>\textbf{Work in groups}</m>
              </p>
              <p>
                 <term>What you need</term>
             </p>
              <p>
                 <ul>
                     <li>
                         <p>   
                             <m>20</m> pieces of marble.
                         </p>
                     </li>
                       <li>
                         <p>
                             <m>4</m> pieces of paper.
                         </p>
                     </li>
                       <li>
                         <p>
                             Pen
                         </p>
                       </li>

                   </ul>
              </p>
             <p>
                 <ol>
                     <li>
                         <p>
                             Under the teachers guidance, the learners to divide
                             themselves in groups of <m>4</m>.
                          </p>
                     </li>
                          <li>
                              <p>
                                  Let each group select a group leader.
                              </p>
                          </li>
                          <li>
                              <p>
                                 Let each group leader from all the groups pick marbles from the teacher,
                                  until the marbles are finished.
                              </p>
                          </li>
                          <li>
                               <p>
                                 Let all members of each group confirm the number of marbles
                                 the leader has.
                               </p>
                         </li>
                              <li>
                                   <p>
                                     The results to be recorded by each group on the different sheets of paper.
                                  </p>
                              </li>
                                 <li>
                                       <p>
                                         The groups to compare their results to see whether they are the same.
                                       </p>
                                 </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            
          </activity>
         <example>
             <statement>
                   <p>
                     Wangechi has 12 pencils. She decides to arrange them in groups of 3.
                     How many pencils were in each group?
                   </p>
             </statement>
             <solution>
                   <p>
                      <md>
                          <mrow> 1\, \text{group} =\amp 3\, \text{pencils} </mrow>
                         <mrow> 12\, \text{pencils}=\amp ? </mrow>
                         <mrow>12 \div 3=\amp 4\, \text{pencils} </mrow>
                      </md> 
                  </p>
             </solution>
         </example>
         <example>
                 <statement>
                      <p>
                         Evaluate : <m>-20 \div -5</m>
                      </p>
                   </statement>
                  <solution>
                     <p>
                          <md>
                                <mrow> -20 \div -5=\amp 4 </mrow>
                          </md>
                      </p>
                  </solution>
            </example>
                    <example>
                         <statement>
                               <p>
                                  Solve : <m>-60 \div 2</m>
                               </p>
                         </statement>
                         <solution>
                              <p>
                                  <md>
                                     <mrow> -60 \div 2=\amp -30 </mrow>
                                  </md>
                              </p>
                        </solution>
                   </example>
                   
         
